            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this sewing calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This sewing calculator combines several tools that sewists
                commonly need but usually have to open on separate websites:
                fabric yardage, circle skirt planning, binding and bias tape,
                and elastic length. It supports both imperial and metric units
                and adds seam and hem allowances automatically.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Fabric yardage for rectangular pieces</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>Fabric yardage</strong> tab assumes you are cutting
                identical rectangles from a bolt of fabric with a given width.
                It first adds seam allowance to your finished dimensions:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Cut width</strong> = finished width + 2 × seam
                  allowance
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Cut length</strong> = finished length + 2 × seam
                  allowance
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Then it estimates how many pieces fit across the fabric width
                and how many rows you need along the length:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Pieces per row</strong> = floor(fabric width ÷ cut
                  width)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Number of rows</strong> = ceil(piece count ÷ pieces
                  per row)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Total fabric length</strong> = rows × cut length</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Finally, it adds your extra percentage for shrinkage or safety
                and converts the result into yards or meters.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Circle skirt calculations</h3>
              <p>
                For circle skirts, the calculator uses the waist measurement to
                compute the radius of the inner circle (waist) and adds skirt
                length and allowances for the outer radius.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>For a full circle skirt:</p>
                <p><strong>Waist radius</strong> = waist ÷ (2π)</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Outer radius</strong> = waist radius + skirt length +
                  hem allowance + waist seam allowance
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Half and quarter circle skirts adjust the waist radius based on
                the angle of the skirt (180° or 90°). The tool then compares the
                required diameter with your fabric width to decide whether the
                skirt fits on a single fold or must be cut in panels.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Binding and bias tape</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>Binding &amp; bias</strong> tab starts from the
                total edge length you want to bind. It adds a small safety
                margin and divides by your fabric width to estimate how many
                strips you need and how much fabric length is required.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Total binding length</strong> = edge length × 1.05 (5%
                  extra)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Number of strips</strong> = ceil(total binding length
                  ÷ fabric width)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Fabric length</strong> = number of strips × strip
                  width
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For true bias binding, the estimate is slightly increased to
                account for diagonal layout and joining losses.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Elastic and waistband</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>Elastic &amp; waistband</strong> tab calculates
                elastic length based on your body measurement, ease, and overlap
                for joining the elastic:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Elastic length</strong> = body measurement + ease +
                  overlap
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>It also suggests a cut height for the waistband casing:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Casing cut height</strong> = 2 × casing finished
                  height + hem/top allowance
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Tips for accurate sewing yardage</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round up generously.</strong> Fabric shops usually cut
                  in 0.25 or 0.5 yard increments; always round up to the next
                  convenient amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider directional prints and nap.</strong> If your
                  fabric has a clear up/down direction or nap (like velvet), you
                  may need extra yardage beyond the geometric estimate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pre-wash when needed.</strong> If you pre-wash fabric,
                  use the shrinkage percentage field or add extra manually.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check pattern layout.</strong> Commercial patterns
                  sometimes require more fabric than simple math suggests due to
                  piece shapes and grainline requirements.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Common sewing questions</h2>
              <h3>How much fabric do I need for a simple gathered skirt?</h3>
              <p>
                For a basic gathered skirt, a common rule of thumb is 1.5–3
                times your waist measurement for the skirt width. You can use
                the Fabric yardage tab by treating the skirt as one or two large
                rectangles: width = waist × fullness factor, length = desired
                skirt length + hem and waistband allowances.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I mix inches and centimeters?</h3>
              <p>
                For best accuracy, pick one system (imperial or metric) and
                stick with it. This calculator lets you switch globally between
                inches/yards and centimeters/meters so all fields stay
                consistent.
              </p>
            </section>

